But for, like, building organizations, it's challenging, right?

00:48:43.919 --> 00:48:51.919
We know of, as you said, those big tech firms, the thought, the stuff that goes through it. And then location has a thing, right? Like, Canada being in the shadow of the United States.

00:48:51.919 --> 00:48:55.919
Like, there's a little bit of that too, right? Like, the poll.

00:48:55.919 --> 00:49:03.919
When I joined Greenshield, I only knew about them because we had healthcare coverage through them before. So I was aware of some of the stuff that they were doing.

00:49:04.919 --> 00:49:09.919
So some of those other industries, similarly to us, is really lower down.

00:49:09.919 --> 00:49:24.919
And the pre-notions and preconceptions of what that means, like insurance or banking or retail, like some of those other sectors that, you know, you don't think of startup or Silicon Valley or, like, those kinds of pieces, it's a challenge.

00:49:24.919 --> 00:49:30.919
So how do we do it? How have I done it? What are some approaches that we're thinking of?

00:49:30.919 --> 00:49:33.919
LinkedIn, first off, be shameless.

00:49:33.919 --> 00:49:37.919
LinkedIn, get as many people as possible.

00:49:37.919 --> 00:49:44.919
I think being a bit edgy and fun, knowing your audience is a bit different rather than we currently have an opportunity.

00:49:44.919 --> 00:49:49.919
No, like, people have so much limited time in their day.

00:49:49.919 --> 00:49:53.919
They want to know what you're really going to be like.

00:49:53.919 --> 00:49:55.919
Like, what's it going to be like? That's where we're at today, right?

00:49:55.919 --> 00:49:58.919
There's a plethora of opportunities.

00:49:58.919 --> 00:50:00.919
So what are some of the things that people are really interested in?

00:50:00.919 --> 00:50:02.919
What are the problems that you're working on?

00:50:02.919 --> 00:50:04.919
Like, that's really interesting.

00:50:04.919 --> 00:50:06.919
A lot of people like to know the tech stack.

00:50:06.919 --> 00:50:13.919
Like, hey, like, am I going to be working on something I'm comfortable with, I'm no longer interested in, or, ooh, that's new, I want to be involved in it.

00:50:13.919 --> 00:50:18.919
So those are some of the pieces that we've used as an approach.

00:50:18.919 --> 00:50:26.919
I think being honest and open is like, hey, we're trying to build stuff, and you're going to have a chance to shape it and, like, organize it and, like, put your thumbprint or your flavor on it.

00:50:26.919 --> 00:50:34.919
So those are some really fun catch pieces to do just for your traditional kind of, like, social media, like, networking parts.

00:50:34.919 --> 00:50:40.919
Where we're going, and I know you and I know where I'm going with what I'm about to say.

00:50:40.919 --> 00:50:50.919
Where we're going is actually making a concerted effort to advertise, and advertise in the sense of giving back to the community.

00:50:50.919 --> 00:51:00.919
So putting out our own analytical blog posts or putting things out on our pubs, putting out media pieces more regularly to show, like, we're doing some fun stuff.

00:51:00.919 --> 00:51:07.919
Yeah, we are not Google, and we don't profess or claim to be, but there's only a couple of those types of places in the world, right?

00:51:07.919 --> 00:51:19.919
So this is the kind of things that we're looking at and putting that out more regularly and contributing to open source so that people can kind of see ahead of time, and then it pops up on their radar.

00:51:19.919 --> 00:51:32.919
Some of the other things that other organizations, in my days in municipal government, go there is changing the titles so that they just pop up on people's searches, right?

00:51:32.919 --> 00:51:42.919
Like, those are some pieces, like, yeah, you may want to use them that way and you bake it in, but people don't necessarily read all the requirements from a search pattern.

00:51:42.919 --> 00:51:50.919
So those would be some pieces, Rachel, if we want to touch and go further, I would be more than happy.

00:51:50.919 --> 00:51:56.919
That's super helpful. I can't wait to also share that snippet with people, too.

00:51:56.919 --> 00:52:08.919
I'm curious from everyone else on the call, too, if there's other things that have worked for you or even specific challenges that you're facing right now with hiring.

00:52:08.919 --> 00:52:16.919
I'm not hiring, but as someone that's looking to get into, we briefly talked about it in the chat last time, I'm 22.

00:52:16.919 --> 00:52:26.919
I'm looking to get into the data science sector, and therefore I look at all these jobs, especially on LinkedIn, where I go, I'm going to be stereotypical about myself.

00:52:26.919 --> 00:52:30.919
I'm white. I'm privileged. I went to a very good school.

00:52:30.919 --> 00:52:39.919
And therefore I see these job applications and posts and I go, I don't care, I'm going to apply anyway. What's the worst that they're going to say no?

00:52:39.919 --> 00:52:43.919
Or don't even respond, probably isn't the worst either.

00:52:43.919 --> 00:52:58.919
So I just apply anyway, but it's found that, and studies have shown that, that hinders a lot of people, especially minorities and people coming from less fortunate backgrounds and applying.

00:52:58.919 --> 00:53:07.919
Do you think generally HR's lack of knowledge about data science sector hinders hiring too much?

00:53:07.919 --> 00:53:11.919
And how do you think that could be a solution to that?

00:53:11.919 --> 00:53:14.919
Yeah.

00:53:14.919 --> 00:53:19.919
I could go into this for hours. My sister's in HR, so we talk about this all the time.

00:53:19.919 --> 00:53:25.919
Generally, when I join an organization, some of the first people I try to make best friends with are the HR people.

00:53:25.919 --> 00:53:32.919
That's just my approach, because if you want to get stuff done, they need to be your best friends.

00:53:32.919 --> 00:53:35.919
They don't know, and they're under the gun for so many different things.

00:53:35.919 --> 00:53:40.919
Hiring is only generally one element of the plethora of HR stuff that goes on.

00:53:40.919 --> 00:53:43.919
So I would say, yeah, they're not sure. They're aware of it.

00:53:43.919 --> 00:53:45.919
They are very aware of the organization.

00:53:45.919 --> 00:53:50.919
They know the story of the sector, how challenging it is.

00:53:50.919 --> 00:53:55.919
What I've done for them is, you know what, I'm going to take some of those costs off for you.

00:53:55.919 --> 00:53:58.919
Send me all of them.

00:53:58.919 --> 00:54:01.919
I don't care if there's 500 applicants.

00:54:01.919 --> 00:54:02.919
Send me every single one of them.

00:54:02.919 --> 00:54:08.919
I will screen with you, and I'll give you my first view, and we'll put some stuff over, and we'll look at it that way.

00:54:08.919 --> 00:54:12.919
Because reading between the lines is sometimes challenging.

00:54:12.919 --> 00:54:21.919
And then also, yeah, they can literally see a language or keyword searches, but within context, it may mean nothing.

00:54:21.919 --> 00:54:27.919
Or if it's like, hey, I did a Udemy course for three hours in this, that doesn't mean you're free to do it.

00:54:27.919 --> 00:54:29.919
So there's some of those pieces.

00:54:29.919 --> 00:54:35.919
So I would say they're critically challenged.

00:54:35.919 --> 00:54:40.919
How I've gone about it is I've taken the costs on to do the recruiting myself.

00:54:40.919 --> 00:54:50.919
I've also, oh, I hope they're not listening, not necessarily followed some of the requirements that I'm supposed to, i.e. education.

00:54:50.919 --> 00:54:55.919
I personally don't care how you got there because it would be very hypocritical of myself.

00:54:55.919 --> 00:54:56.919
I didn't follow that path.

00:54:56.919 --> 00:55:01.919
I think we live in a world where there isn't a defined path, and people can get there lots of different ways.

00:55:01.919 --> 00:55:08.919
So there's a lot of other pieces that we do to screen people in and look at it.

00:55:08.919 --> 00:55:12.919
One of my favorite teams that I've ever worked on was at the City of Open Data.

00:55:12.919 --> 00:55:21.919
And for those of you who haven't watched Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, the 1960 stop motion one, watch it afterwards because this comment I'm about to say will make more sense.

00:55:21.919 --> 00:55:23.919
We were the island of misfit toys.

00:55:23.919 --> 00:55:30.919
We were nowhere close to your stereotypical superstar team, but boy, oh, boy, did we get a lot of stuff done.

00:55:30.919 --> 00:55:37.919
And typical HR people wouldn't be able to find those meshes and nuances of how the jigsaw puzzle of success would go together.

00:55:37.919 --> 00:55:46.919
So I think sharing some of those costs as in, like, work and screening really behooves us as people who are building teams to work with HR that way.

00:55:46.919 --> 00:55:48.919
How would we get there?

00:55:48.919 --> 00:55:57.919
I think it goes back a bit of your question earlier, Zach, because a tech person who wants to make a career change and go into that field and bring that domain knowledge in,

00:55:57.919 --> 00:56:03.919
but HR is somewhat, like us, has some rigid requirements to be able to get in because there's apps and laws and other pieces.

00:56:04.919 --> 00:56:11.919
I think it's going to be a challenge for us for a decade more.

00:56:11.919 --> 00:56:13.919
Thank you very much.

00:56:13.919 --> 00:56:16.919
No problem.

00:56:16.919 --> 00:56:19.919
I see a lot of great comments in the chat right now.

00:56:19.919 --> 00:56:22.919
And Sep, I see you just raised your hand if you want to jump in first.

00:56:22.919 --> 00:56:26.919
Yeah, if you don't mind, I was just going to kind of add on to that.

00:56:26.919 --> 00:56:30.919
There's a whole spectrum of companies, Zach, and for other people.

00:56:30.919 --> 00:56:32.919
And it kind of depends on your bandwidth, too.

00:56:32.919 --> 00:56:39.919
Like, I think at prior companies, I didn't really have the bandwidth to go through all the applications primarily because the company is so large, right?

00:56:39.919 --> 00:56:48.919
When it's, like, 10,000-plus employees, they have very kind of strict ways of how they handle applications and things of that nature.

00:56:48.919 --> 00:56:55.919
And it was actually quite a struggle because as much as I would try to explain to the recruiter to filter these things,

00:56:55.919 --> 00:57:02.919
there was always a computer that's always in front that allows some of these applications to get through because people are just throwing in a bunch of keywords.

00:57:02.919 --> 00:57:05.919
And the recruiter then sees it and then passes it along to you.

00:57:05.919 --> 00:57:07.919
And I'm like, this doesn't mean anything to me.

00:57:07.919 --> 00:57:09.919
I can't do anything with this.

00:57:09.919 --> 00:57:18.919
So, you know, my recommendation, especially if you're trying to break into the area, is be very specific about what it is that you want to do,

00:57:18.919 --> 00:57:24.919
what area you want to work in, and reach out to those people that you find interesting on LinkedIn or whatnot.

00:57:24.919 --> 00:57:32.919
And just send them a message asking just to chat with them because a lot of times you find that there may be a match in personality or in education,

00:57:32.919 --> 00:57:38.919
and then that allows you to kind of circumvent this kind of somewhat broken process with larger companies.

00:57:38.919 --> 00:57:42.919
So that was just one of the kind of put those two cents out there.

00:57:42.919 --> 00:57:43.919
That's awesome.

00:57:43.919 --> 00:57:48.919
And then just to add on to that, if there's not a fit with the person you reach out to, generally they have a network,

00:57:48.919 --> 00:57:52.919
and we always try to help each other out so we'll point people in other directions as well.

00:57:52.919 --> 00:57:56.919
So I think it's always a great concept to just reach out.

00:57:56.919 --> 00:57:57.919
Yeah.

00:57:57.919 --> 00:57:58.919
Oh, definitely.

00:57:58.919 --> 00:57:59.919
Thank you.

00:57:59.919 --> 00:58:05.919
I'm going to chime in and pile on to everything Sep said, especially at larger companies.

00:58:05.919 --> 00:58:08.919
Like a good strategy is hit me up on LinkedIn.

00:58:08.919 --> 00:58:13.919
Our recruiting process isn't always as robust as you might think it is.

00:58:13.919 --> 00:58:17.919
Yep.

00:58:18.919 --> 00:58:29.919
Mike, I see you had a great point in the chat as well, if you'd like to jump in and add that.

00:58:29.919 --> 00:58:31.919
Hi.

00:58:31.919 --> 00:58:35.919
I'm starting to think about this kind of process as well.

00:58:35.919 --> 00:58:43.919
And at my company we had talked about the potential for growing data scientists.

00:58:44.919 --> 00:58:53.919
So bringing in people who kind of demonstrate the right kind of enthusiasm, the right kind of data focus and analytical thinking,

00:58:53.919 --> 00:58:56.919
maybe not necessarily the tech skills.

00:58:56.919 --> 00:59:01.919
And almost doing an apprenticeship and saying, you know, we realize that you don't know everything yet.

00:59:01.919 --> 00:59:03.919
That's cool.

00:59:03.919 --> 00:59:05.919
But we'll show you how.

00:59:05.919 --> 00:59:10.919
And, you know, after a period, if you realize that it's not for you, that's great.

00:59:11.919 --> 00:59:14.919
We'll send you on your way with a pat on the back.

00:59:14.919 --> 00:59:17.919
But if you find that you love it, then great.

00:59:17.919 --> 00:59:19.919
Carry on.

00:59:19.919 --> 00:59:27.919
And I wonder whether that's a more sustainable model than, you know, continuing to hunt for the unicorns.

00:59:27.919 --> 00:59:30.919
Yeah.

00:59:30.919 --> 00:59:31.919
I promise I'll be quick.

00:59:31.919 --> 00:59:33.919
I'll add and then let others too.

00:59:33.919 --> 00:59:35.919
I think that's how we're going to see stuff going.

00:59:35.919 --> 00:59:39.919
And we're looking at doing that very similarly at Greenshield ourselves.

00:59:39.919 --> 00:59:41.919
Do a little company plug.

00:59:41.919 --> 00:59:42.919
But we're doing transformations.

00:59:42.919 --> 00:59:43.919
And you're seeing that.

00:59:43.919 --> 00:59:47.919
And we saw it in other places, this operational model, like operating model.

00:59:47.919 --> 00:59:49.919
And I know not all organizations do that.

00:59:49.919 --> 00:59:50.919
But the hub and spoke.

00:59:50.919 --> 00:59:53.919
You may have your core place that is the core.

00:59:53.919 --> 00:59:57.919
But now starting to put people in other organizations that are data focused.

00:59:57.919 --> 00:59:59.919
Places know that we need to do this.

00:59:59.919 --> 01:00:00.919
We need to transition.

01:00:00.919 --> 01:00:01.919
Right?

01:00:01.919 --> 01:00:08.919
So putting that in there and having a strong educational kind of mentorship piece, I think, is how we will grow it.

01:00:08.919 --> 01:00:14.919
And just being really realistic on we're not trying to grow unicorns.

01:00:14.919 --> 01:00:19.919
We're trying to grow people that can solve problems that are valuable to our business.

01:00:19.919 --> 01:00:22.919
I think it's like if we know going into that, you're not going to count a unicorn.

01:00:22.919 --> 01:00:24.919
We don't expect you to be that.

01:00:24.919 --> 01:00:32.919
Then I think that model is going to work superb.

01:00:32.919 --> 01:00:36.919
And Ryan, I'd love to just also have you share the roles that you're hiring for too.

01:00:36.919 --> 01:00:39.919
And I realize there was a question that I missed earlier.

01:00:39.919 --> 01:00:45.919
If all the roles would be for people in Canada or.

01:00:45.919 --> 01:00:47.919
So we have a hybrid working model.

01:00:47.919 --> 01:00:50.919
I think we're Canadian only focus.

01:00:50.919 --> 01:00:51.919
I'd have to check.

01:00:51.919 --> 01:00:55.919
And I'm not sure if that has to do with, like, taxation kind of purposes.

01:00:55.919 --> 01:00:56.919
I'm not sure.

01:00:56.919 --> 01:01:00.919
We're a Canadian company, but we definitely have American clients.

01:01:00.919 --> 01:01:01.919
Like, I know that.

01:01:01.919 --> 01:01:03.919
So I would say apply anyways.

01:01:03.919 --> 01:01:08.919
Like, if you're interested, we currently have two of our data engineering piece.

01:01:08.919 --> 01:01:09.919
What does that mean?

01:01:09.919 --> 01:01:15.919
It's like your data pipelines, building access points, APIs.

01:01:15.919 --> 01:01:18.919
They'll always be working with, like, analytical kind of pieces,

01:01:18.919 --> 01:01:22.919
but really shaping up and building that kind of that whole practice.

01:01:22.919 --> 01:01:25.919
Because it's missing in a lot of organizations.

01:01:25.919 --> 01:01:27.919
So we're focusing there.

01:01:27.919 --> 01:01:31.919
We have more that will be coming up soon in that true data science.

01:01:31.919 --> 01:01:33.919
And this is where that split is.

01:01:33.919 --> 01:01:36.919
So for those of you who love that word and think that's you,

01:01:36.919 --> 01:01:38.919
we won't be asking you to do data planning.

01:01:38.919 --> 01:01:40.919
That's the data engineering.

01:01:40.919 --> 01:01:44.919
You're going to be focusing on doing analytics and building models.

01:01:44.919 --> 01:01:48.919
And then where we're going to be looking into the new year a little bit more

01:01:48.919 --> 01:01:50.919
is, like, that more machine learning engineer.

01:01:50.919 --> 01:01:52.919
So you as a data scientist can take it to a certain level

01:01:52.919 --> 01:01:55.919
and then hand it off to, like, a machine learning engineering person

01:01:55.919 --> 01:01:56.919
to harden it up.

01:01:56.919 --> 01:02:02.919
So we're really trying to build things kind of, I don't want to say siloed,

01:02:02.919 --> 01:02:05.919
but more focused onto, like, your skill sets and your interests

01:02:05.919 --> 01:02:07.919
and putting it there.

01:02:07.919 --> 01:02:12.919
And then also I'm a firm believer of putting in more starting out roles,

01:02:12.919 --> 01:02:14.919
like in that analyst level, so people can grow up.

01:02:14.919 --> 01:02:19.919
And I'm trying to start pushing into, like, that data storyteller,

01:02:19.919 --> 01:02:22.919
data journalist, product analyst that's doing the communication

01:02:22.919 --> 01:02:28.919
and starting to put that in there instead of our typical BA, business analyst.

01:02:28.919 --> 01:02:30.919
So those are some of the things that we're doing.

01:02:30.919 --> 01:02:35.919
We have a really big initiative for analytics in 2022 to 2025,

01:02:35.919 --> 01:02:38.919
so keep your eyes on us.

01:02:38.919 --> 01:02:39.919
You'll see a lot.

01:02:39.919 --> 01:02:41.919
And if you follow me on LinkedIn, I'm going to bug you

01:02:41.919 --> 01:02:44.919
because you're going to see a lot of stuff coming out.

01:02:44.919 --> 01:02:45.919
Awesome.

01:02:45.919 --> 01:02:46.919
Thank you so much, Ryan.

01:02:46.919 --> 01:02:52.919
And I know a few people have to drop because we just went over the hour mark.

01:02:52.919 --> 01:02:57.919
So I do want to say thank you so much to everybody for being a part of this

01:02:57.919 --> 01:03:00.919
community and building the Data Science Hangout this year.

01:03:00.919 --> 01:03:03.919
This has really turned into my favorite part of the week,

01:03:03.919 --> 01:03:05.919
being able to hang out with you all.

01:03:05.919 --> 01:03:06.919
So thank you.

01:03:06.919 --> 01:03:10.919
And wishing everybody happy holiday and a happy new year.

01:03:10.919 --> 01:03:14.919
Looking forward to seeing you all back on January 6th.

01:03:14.919 --> 01:03:17.919
I definitely want to stay on and ask a few other questions,

01:03:17.919 --> 01:03:19.919
if you have a few more minutes, Ryan.

01:03:19.919 --> 01:03:20.919
Yeah, I totally do.

01:03:20.919 --> 01:03:23.919
I actually am on a day off, so I've got hours.

01:03:23.919 --> 01:03:26.919
Thank you for joining us on your day off.

01:03:26.919 --> 01:03:29.919
Yeah, no, I've been looking forward to this for a long time.

01:03:29.919 --> 01:03:30.919
Awesome.

01:03:30.919 --> 01:03:34.919
Well, also, I shared a feedback form as well in the chat,

01:03:34.919 --> 01:03:37.919
if anyone wants to take a look at that and give feedback

01:03:37.919 --> 01:03:41.919
or suggestions for next year, as well as our speaker lineup.

01:03:41.919 --> 01:03:45.919
But, Peter, I saw you also put a great question in the chat when we were

01:03:45.919 --> 01:03:51.919
talking about hiring, around hiring in the public sector.

01:03:51.919 --> 01:03:58.919
Would you want to jump in there?

01:03:58.919 --> 01:04:00.919
And, Peter, I can read it.

01:04:00.919 --> 01:04:05.919
And if you want to just add more context, feel free to jump in, too.

01:04:05.919 --> 01:04:09.919
But the question was, one issue we have in the public sector is recruiting

01:04:09.919 --> 01:04:13.919
when our hiring process is so slow, it makes us less competitive

01:04:13.919 --> 01:04:16.919
and drawing in people actively seeking a position.

01:04:16.919 --> 01:04:19.919
Just interested in any thoughts on that.

01:04:19.919 --> 01:04:20.919
Oh, my gosh, Peter.

01:04:20.919 --> 01:04:23.919
That was five years for me at the City of Toronto.

01:04:23.919 --> 01:04:26.919
Like, creating a role took two years.

01:04:26.919 --> 01:04:27.919
So, like, I get it.

01:04:27.919 --> 01:04:33.919
And, like, people told me, you got a job filled in six months?

01:04:33.919 --> 01:04:35.919
How were you able to do that so fast?

01:04:35.919 --> 01:04:37.919
And I was able to start doing it in three.

01:04:37.919 --> 01:04:39.919
And they're like, how does it work?

01:04:39.919 --> 01:04:41.919
Like, how are you doing that?

01:04:41.919 --> 01:04:44.919
And not to say that we did it all the time.

01:04:44.919 --> 01:04:46.919
I had many jobs that went to, like, three rounds.

01:04:46.919 --> 01:04:48.919
Like, it's extremely slow.

01:04:48.919 --> 01:04:51.919
So, how do we do the competitiveness?

01:04:51.919 --> 01:04:53.919
One thing that I will put out there, I was lucky.

01:04:53.919 --> 01:04:55.919
City of Toronto is a big name, right?

01:04:55.919 --> 01:04:57.919
Like, we are a target.

01:04:57.919 --> 01:04:59.919
We have a brand associated to it.

01:04:59.919 --> 01:05:01.919
So, that did help us.

01:05:01.919 --> 01:05:05.919
Like, I will say that that was a positive thing that helped us.

01:05:05.919 --> 01:05:08.919
Early on, it was hard.

01:05:08.919 --> 01:05:09.919
It was extremely hard.

01:05:09.919 --> 01:05:16.919
And what I learned where we started to get more qualified applicants,

01:05:16.919 --> 01:05:17.919
if you want to say it that way,

01:05:17.919 --> 01:05:20.919
more interest from people that you would not expect,

01:05:20.919 --> 01:05:25.919
and then just more applicants, was that advertising.

01:05:25.919 --> 01:05:28.919
Like, what you're doing, right?

01:05:28.919 --> 01:05:30.919
So, I joined.

01:05:30.919 --> 01:05:33.919
I joined the City of Toronto midway through my Ph.D.

01:05:33.919 --> 01:05:35.919
and decided not to finish and went there.

01:05:35.919 --> 01:05:37.919
And people were like, you're committing suicide.

01:05:37.919 --> 01:05:38.919
What are you doing?

01:05:38.919 --> 01:05:39.919
You're going to, like, a large bureaucracy.

01:05:39.919 --> 01:05:42.919
And I'm like, I see it differently.

01:05:42.919 --> 01:05:46.919
I see it as an opportunity to make municipal government like it was in the

01:05:46.919 --> 01:05:49.919
60s and 70s, where they were doing the cool stuff,

01:05:49.919 --> 01:05:52.919
where they were doing all the solving of the problems.

01:05:52.919 --> 01:05:57.919
And I looked at it as, hey, I joined as a manager, a title.

01:05:57.919 --> 01:05:58.919
I'm not a title person.

01:05:58.919 --> 01:06:00.919
But I had a team of, like, 30 people.

01:06:00.919 --> 01:06:02.919
That means I have an operating budget.

01:06:02.919 --> 01:06:04.919
How is that any different than having a grad program?

01:06:04.919 --> 01:06:06.919
I didn't have to recruit any grad students.

01:06:06.919 --> 01:06:08.919
I had people there, and I had guaranteed funding.

01:06:08.919 --> 01:06:09.919
I didn't have to write things.

01:06:09.919 --> 01:06:11.919
So, if you take a look at it a little bit differently,

01:06:11.919 --> 01:06:16.919
and you play within your rules, and I kind of throw the rules out,

01:06:16.919 --> 01:06:17.919
in the municipal government, Peter,

01:06:17.919 --> 01:06:23.919
one thing that I would say is get to know your severance package policy

01:06:23.919 --> 01:06:27.919
really well because you'll realize that it takes them a long time to get you

01:06:27.919 --> 01:06:32.919
out, and in the public sector, delivery trumps everything.

01:06:32.919 --> 01:06:41.919
So, what we did is we asked for forgiveness and didn't ask for permission,

01:06:41.919 --> 01:06:42.919
right?

01:06:42.919 --> 01:06:47.919
So, we started to just take over social media kind of stuff and putting things

01:06:47.919 --> 01:06:50.919
out, talking about what we specifically were doing,

01:06:50.919 --> 01:06:53.919
what it's going to be like to come there, and then we delivered.

01:06:53.919 --> 01:06:57.919
And we delivered quickly, and we didn't deliver perfectly.

01:06:57.919 --> 01:07:02.919
And that has a bit of a purpose, one, because it's pragmatic.

01:07:02.919 --> 01:07:04.919
It's impossible to deliver perfectly.

01:07:04.919 --> 01:07:07.919
But people see things quicker, and they see things often,

01:07:07.919 --> 01:07:12.919
and then they also start to dispel this kind of preconceived conception of,

01:07:12.919 --> 01:07:17.919
like, bureaucracy and slow and boring and things like that.

01:07:17.919 --> 01:07:19.919
And we started to get out and speak.

01:07:19.919 --> 01:07:21.919
We would go to events, and it didn't have to be me.

01:07:21.919 --> 01:07:23.919
It could be people on the team and go out.

01:07:23.919 --> 01:07:26.919
Like, people will resonate and talk about stuff and put the word out there.

01:07:26.919 --> 01:07:29.919
And then joining into the open source community and, like,

01:07:29.919 --> 01:07:34.919
really pushing that on the inside and doing stuff got people to be like,

01:07:34.919 --> 01:07:37.919
oh, government's doing some kind of cool stuff here.

01:07:37.919 --> 01:07:38.919
Like, I'm interested in that.

01:07:38.919 --> 01:07:44.919
And then the thing that we always have that private sector doesn't have all the

01:07:44.919 --> 01:07:46.919
time is we're doing stuff that helps society.

01:07:46.919 --> 01:07:49.919
And there are certain elements of people who really look for that

01:07:49.919 --> 01:07:51.919
and really want to align themselves.

01:07:51.919 --> 01:07:56.919
And we actually had a ton of people who were leaving the big five large

01:07:56.919 --> 01:07:59.919
tech companies who were like, I made a lot of money,

01:07:59.919 --> 01:08:03.919
but I didn't do a lot of good for what they were thinking.

01:08:03.919 --> 01:08:06.919
I'm not saying that they didn't do good, but from what they were saying,

01:08:06.919 --> 01:08:09.919
I didn't do anything that was helping what they envisioned for values in

01:08:09.919 --> 01:08:12.919
their societal kind of lens and what's important to them.

01:08:12.919 --> 01:08:14.919
So they wanted to transition into that.

01:08:15.919 --> 01:08:18.919
So by making that just known in your postings and, like,

01:08:18.919 --> 01:08:21.919
the way that you share it out there and having, like,

01:08:21.919 --> 01:08:24.919
advertising, like, your social media presence, like,

01:08:24.919 --> 01:08:26.919
this is what we're going to do and this is what we stand for,

01:08:26.919 --> 01:08:28.919
that attracts people.

01:08:28.919 --> 01:08:30.919
That allows people to be like, okay, I'm going to go make a difference,

01:08:30.919 --> 01:08:33.919
and this is how I can see that I'm going to do it,

01:08:33.919 --> 01:08:35.919
and these are the things that are going to do it.

01:08:35.919 --> 01:08:38.919
I'm going to wait.

01:08:38.919 --> 01:08:40.919
It's going to be worth it.

01:08:40.919 --> 01:08:43.919
It's totally going to be worth it to wait, and that's okay.

01:08:44.919 --> 01:08:47.919
The other shameless thing, Peter, and I'm already saying this now,

01:08:47.919 --> 01:08:50.919
because I'm no longer a public employee, oh, I stalked people.

01:08:50.919 --> 01:08:53.919
I stalked people.

01:08:53.919 --> 01:08:57.919
My buddy, Matt Tenney, I straight-up stalked him.

01:08:57.919 --> 01:08:59.919
And, like, we hired him,

01:08:59.919 --> 01:09:02.919
and he was our first true data scientist at the City of Toronto.

01:09:02.919 --> 01:09:05.919
I stalked him and stalked him and stalked him online and pulled him away

01:09:05.919 --> 01:09:07.919
from, like, Esri Canada.

01:09:07.919 --> 01:09:09.919
So it was something.

01:09:09.919 --> 01:09:10.919
And another municipality.

01:09:10.919 --> 01:09:11.919
He was looking at other things.

01:09:11.919 --> 01:09:13.919
So if you're on there, Matt, if you hear this, ha-ha.

01:09:13.919 --> 01:09:17.919
Remember those days back in 2017.

01:09:17.919 --> 01:09:19.919
Those are some of the approaches that we used,

01:09:19.919 --> 01:09:24.919
and I was okay with it because I knew how long it was going to take

01:09:24.919 --> 01:09:26.919
and how much it was going to cost him to fire me.

01:09:26.919 --> 01:09:28.919
So that's what I mean by the sevens package.

01:09:28.919 --> 01:09:31.919
So, like, you have some really good trump cards that you can play

01:09:31.919 --> 01:09:37.919
in public sector, but it's hard, really hard.

01:09:37.919 --> 01:09:38.919
Thank you.

01:09:38.919 --> 01:09:39.919
That's very helpful,

01:09:39.919 --> 01:09:42.919
and I feel like we're really trying to do something very similar

01:09:42.919 --> 01:09:48.919
and develop capacity in-house, you know, and do more with our data.

01:09:48.919 --> 01:09:51.919
And I think we are doing some interesting things,

01:09:51.919 --> 01:09:53.919
and we have some interesting things on the horizon.

01:09:53.919 --> 01:09:57.919
But I've just found in, you know, many different hiring cycles,

01:09:57.919 --> 01:09:59.919
not just for data positions,

01:09:59.919 --> 01:10:01.919
but, like, by the time we get around to hiring somebody,

01:10:01.919 --> 01:10:06.919
we've lost half of our interview panel because they found other positions.

01:10:07.919 --> 01:10:11.919
I like this idea of having, you know, because three to six months,

01:10:11.919 --> 01:10:12.919
that is kind of the window,

01:10:12.919 --> 01:10:16.919
but that's too long for somebody who is looking for a position now.

01:10:16.919 --> 01:10:20.919
And so I appreciate some of the strategies

01:10:20.919 --> 01:10:22.919
that we can kind of wrap around that.

01:10:22.919 --> 01:10:23.919
Thank you.

01:10:23.919 --> 01:10:24.919
No problem.

01:10:24.919 --> 01:10:27.919
The other thing that we did because we weren't able to hire because,

01:10:27.919 --> 01:10:29.919
like, the talent was just so hard

01:10:29.919 --> 01:10:33.919
or waiting for budget cycles to come through to create new positions,

01:10:33.919 --> 01:10:35.919
we did something really bold.

01:10:35.919 --> 01:10:39.919
We took an entire team who were 55 to 63 years old

01:10:39.919 --> 01:10:42.919
and sent them to school for two months.

01:10:42.919 --> 01:10:44.919
And straight up sent them out.

01:10:44.919 --> 01:10:45.919
So you're going to school.

01:10:45.919 --> 01:10:47.919
It was York University, so I'll give a plug to them.

01:10:47.919 --> 01:10:48.919
They did a great job.

01:10:48.919 --> 01:10:51.919
And they were in school for five days a week to re-educate them,

01:10:51.919 --> 01:10:54.919
and they went through a whole data science program kind of piece.

01:10:54.919 --> 01:10:56.919
It was a tough sell, but it means that I

01:10:56.919 --> 01:11:00.919
and a few other people took on those costs of doing some of the jobs,

01:11:00.919 --> 01:11:02.919
like organizing, working with the business to say,

01:11:02.919 --> 01:11:04.919
we're going to be a little bit of a lull on our delivery,

01:11:04.919 --> 01:11:06.919
but here's what you're going to get on the end.

01:11:06.919 --> 01:11:12.919
So that might help you as a different strategy as well of tooling up

01:11:12.919 --> 01:11:14.919
if you can't recruit, like, as a piece.

01:11:14.919 --> 01:11:16.919
Because let's be honest,

01:11:16.919 --> 01:11:20.919
side of your desk education is really hard at the beginning for people.

01:11:20.919 --> 01:11:22.919
I think that's a great way to top up and improve

01:11:22.919 --> 01:11:25.919
when you already have that confidence and those capabilities,

01:11:25.919 --> 01:11:27.919
those tool sets in your toolbox, right?

01:11:27.919 --> 01:11:29.919
You might have a hammer and a screwdriver,

01:11:29.919 --> 01:11:31.919
but after a while you start needing other tools.

01:11:31.919 --> 01:11:37.919
And that's easier when you have those bases.

01:11:37.919 --> 01:11:39.919
I'm not sure if that's something of interest, Peter,

01:11:39.919 --> 01:11:41.919
but we found it really helpful.

01:11:41.919 --> 01:11:44.919
And boy, were those individuals super grateful.

01:11:44.919 --> 01:11:49.919
And they went from low performers to high performers overnight.

01:11:49.919 --> 01:11:53.919
And it sparked other people in the team and the organization,

01:11:53.919 --> 01:11:54.919
like, I want to do that too.

01:11:54.919 --> 01:12:00.919
And it just starts to change the culture of, like, what's acceptable.

01:12:00.919 --> 01:12:05.919
Because output sells.

01:12:05.919 --> 01:12:07.919
Mubanga, I see you have your hand raised as well.

01:12:07.919 --> 01:12:10.919
I'd love to turn it over to you.

01:12:10.919 --> 01:12:11.919
Thanks, Rachel.

01:12:11.919 --> 01:12:13.919
I just have a quick question on RAM.

01:12:13.919 --> 01:12:16.919
What O'Reilly book is there on your shelf?

01:12:16.919 --> 01:12:25.919
What's O'Reilly?

01:12:25.919 --> 01:12:30.919
So do you want to go chronologically, alphabetical, or just off the top?

01:12:30.919 --> 01:12:35.919
I was interested in the one that was on the far right, the white O'Reilly book.

01:12:35.919 --> 01:12:37.919
This one?

01:12:37.919 --> 01:12:38.919
Yes.

01:12:38.919 --> 01:12:40.919
Oh, okay.

01:12:40.919 --> 01:12:44.919
Yeah, that's my most recent read.

01:12:44.919 --> 01:12:48.919
This is how it all began.

01:12:48.919 --> 01:12:50.919
This is what I used in grad school.

01:12:50.919 --> 01:12:55.919
So if you're a qualitative geographer, this was really helpful.

01:12:55.919 --> 01:12:59.919
I'll be honest, this one was over my head a lot.

01:12:59.919 --> 01:13:03.919
And then ggplot, I still have to look up the syntax.

01:13:03.919 --> 01:13:06.919
I read this one on the TTC on the subway.

01:13:06.919 --> 01:13:10.919
It was just, like, a long commute.

01:13:10.919 --> 01:13:12.919
Awesome book.

01:13:12.919 --> 01:13:15.919
This is really well done.

01:13:15.919 --> 01:13:19.919
Super helpful because this is, like, where I'm starting to progress now

01:13:19.919 --> 01:13:23.919
is to improve access for people so they don't need to know everything.

01:13:23.919 --> 01:13:25.919
They can just access through a package.

01:13:25.919 --> 01:13:31.919
And then for my geo friends, it doesn't get any better than this.

01:13:31.919 --> 01:13:32.919
Thank you, Ryan.

01:13:32.919 --> 01:13:39.919
You're reminding me that we talked about maybe having a book club at some point.

01:13:39.919 --> 01:13:42.919
One other question that I see that we have remaining,

01:13:42.919 --> 01:13:47.919
and if there's any others that I maybe missed in the chat, please jump in.

01:13:48.919 --> 01:13:52.919
Bruno, I see you had a great question.

01:13:52.919 --> 01:13:54.919
Well, I won't summarize.

01:13:54.919 --> 01:13:56.919
I'll turn it over to you.

01:13:56.919 --> 01:13:57.919
All right.

01:13:57.919 --> 01:14:02.919
Ryan, I really like the way you speak, how you interpret the business word.

01:14:02.919 --> 01:14:07.919
How did you develop such interesting views around business and people interaction?

01:14:07.919 --> 01:14:09.919
Do you have mentors?

01:14:09.919 --> 01:14:14.919
Was it trial and error?

01:14:14.919 --> 01:14:16.919
Believe it or not, I don't take compliments very well,

01:14:16.919 --> 01:14:19.919
so that's really flattering and hard for me to, like, digest.

01:14:19.919 --> 01:14:21.919
So thank you so much, Bruno.

01:14:21.919 --> 01:14:27.919
If I reflect back, trial and tribulation,

01:14:27.919 --> 01:14:31.919
I don't have, like, your normal progressional path through things.

01:14:31.919 --> 01:14:35.919
I moved around a whole bunch, like, my whole life.

01:14:35.919 --> 01:14:37.919
I literally have moved 50 times in my life.

01:14:37.919 --> 01:14:40.919
So it's been forcing me to have to speak.

01:14:40.919 --> 01:14:43.919
So I think early on, if I think about it, that really did it.

01:14:43.919 --> 01:14:48.919
Another thing for me, I had an early on job where I gave gondola tours.

01:14:48.919 --> 01:14:52.919
And I was stuck in a gondola with 50 people and had to talk to them.

01:14:52.919 --> 01:14:54.919
And a lot of times a gondola would get stuck over a river,

01:14:54.919 --> 01:14:55.919
and we could be there for 20 minutes.

01:14:55.919 --> 01:14:59.919
So it would really force you to talk.

01:14:59.919 --> 01:15:06.919
I would say what truly helped me transition into the speaking is my love of movies

01:15:06.919 --> 01:15:11.919
and trying to break things down into a movie.

01:15:11.919 --> 01:15:15.919
It's very visual, but movies tell a story.

01:15:15.919 --> 01:15:19.919
And people love stories.

01:15:19.919 --> 01:15:26.919
So if you can kind of remove the jargon for a bit,

01:15:26.919 --> 01:15:29.919
and I do pick that word because a lot of business leaders think, like,

01:15:29.919 --> 01:15:30.919
oh, here we go, jargon.

01:15:30.919 --> 01:15:32.919
They're coming in with jargon again.

01:15:32.919 --> 01:15:39.919
It's to remove that and be vulnerable and allow people to be part of your story

01:15:39.919 --> 01:15:43.919
and reward them.

01:15:43.919 --> 01:15:46.919
So telling them and bringing them involved and helping them be part of it.

01:15:46.919 --> 01:15:50.919
So I think following the script of, like, some of your favorite movies

01:15:50.919 --> 01:15:52.919
or just, like, how I've done it.

01:15:52.919 --> 01:15:54.919
It's like, let's be animated.

01:15:54.919 --> 01:15:56.919
I don't mind being silly.

01:15:56.919 --> 01:15:58.919
Hence, what I'm wearing is what I'm wearing.

01:15:58.919 --> 01:16:02.919
Like, I have no problem with it.

01:16:02.919 --> 01:16:07.919
Through my progression is if we keep going, some of the pieces that go along

01:16:07.919 --> 01:16:09.919
is truly being vulnerable.

01:16:09.919 --> 01:16:13.919
And then my wife, she's my sounding board.

01:16:13.919 --> 01:16:17.919
Prior to that, I had a great friend that I worked with, Mike, at Sanborn,

01:16:17.919 --> 01:16:20.919
and we were doing Geo stuff, and we were building products.

01:16:20.919 --> 01:16:21.919
And he's like, I'm a designer.

01:16:21.919 --> 01:16:23.919
I draw.

01:16:23.919 --> 01:16:25.919
So I would use him as a sounding board.

01:16:25.919 --> 01:16:28.919
If Mike didn't get it, no one would.

01:16:28.919 --> 01:16:30.919
So, like, having those kinds of pieces.

01:16:30.919 --> 01:16:33.919
So using my wife, like, does this make sense?

01:16:33.919 --> 01:16:37.919
Like, she's a teacher, and she teaches elementary school students,

01:16:37.919 --> 01:16:39.919
so nothing in this space.

01:16:39.919 --> 01:16:41.919
So she's like, yeah, I get it.

01:16:41.919 --> 01:16:42.919
Is this what it is?

01:16:42.919 --> 01:16:43.919
I'm like, okay.

01:16:43.919 --> 01:16:47.919
Changing the approach, and then I went into, like, analogies.

01:16:47.919 --> 01:16:51.919
So I think having kind of a dynamic kind of way about stuff

01:16:51.919 --> 01:16:57.919
and trying to understand your audience and somewhat into groups

01:16:57.919 --> 01:17:00.919
and what is really important for them.

01:17:00.919 --> 01:17:04.919
So some people have true importance on just pure profit.

01:17:04.919 --> 01:17:07.919
Like, okay, I'm going to use profit kind of directions of my story.

01:17:07.919 --> 01:17:11.919
Some people are about, like, no, no, no, how's the culture and the feel?

01:17:11.919 --> 01:17:14.919
So you kind of mitigate and you swing around.

01:17:14.919 --> 01:17:17.919
A friend of mine told me, and I took offense to it right away,

01:17:17.919 --> 01:17:19.919
and then I was like, oh, wait, no, that's not offensive.

01:17:19.919 --> 01:17:20.919
You're a chameleon, right?

01:17:20.919 --> 01:17:22.919
And it's funny that I bring that up.

01:17:22.919 --> 01:17:24.919
My son was asking me, what's a chameleon?

01:17:24.919 --> 01:17:26.919
I'm like, oh, how do I explain that to a 4-year-old?

01:17:26.919 --> 01:17:29.919
It's a lizard that changes color within their environment.

01:17:29.919 --> 01:17:30.919
They adapt.

01:17:30.919 --> 01:17:34.919
And I think that's kind of a bit of the essence is adapting to your environment

01:17:34.919 --> 01:17:39.919
and understanding what people value and appreciate.

01:17:39.919 --> 01:17:45.919
And if you can somewhat get there on a common level ground,

01:17:45.919 --> 01:17:51.919
people appreciate that because there are people who want that hardcore tech

01:17:51.919 --> 01:17:55.919
and they were like, every time you speak it, you better be giving me your resume.

01:17:55.919 --> 01:17:57.919
Like, there are those individuals there,

01:17:57.919 --> 01:17:59.919
and they're always going to be at that level.

01:17:59.919 --> 01:18:02.919
And then there's the far other end of the spectrum of people.

01:18:02.919 --> 01:18:04.919
It's like, I'm too afraid to kind of like ask anything.

01:18:04.919 --> 01:18:06.919
That's just not who they are.

01:18:06.919 --> 01:18:11.919
People are somewhere in the middle, and most people, you know, nerd,

01:18:11.919 --> 01:18:17.919
normal distribution, most people are somewhere in the middle.

01:18:17.919 --> 01:18:19.919
We get off-put, right?

01:18:19.919 --> 01:18:24.919
It's like, are you seriously resuming me right now?

01:18:24.919 --> 01:18:27.919
Like, is that how we're doing this conversation?

01:18:27.919 --> 01:18:30.919
So kind of breaking it down so that people can feel like they have something

01:18:30.919 --> 01:18:33.919
to contribute and like, oh, I'm a little bit higher than that.

01:18:33.919 --> 01:18:35.919
Like, yes, great, and they're giving.

01:18:35.919 --> 01:18:41.919
I think doing that and not feeling like – I'm not saying you are.

01:18:41.919 --> 01:18:45.919
Just one of the things that I kind of try to do, and I don't do it well all the time,

01:18:45.919 --> 01:18:47.919
is letting people give more than what you are.

01:18:47.919 --> 01:18:52.919
You facilitate kind of the dialogue and let people feel like they're giving.

01:18:52.919 --> 01:18:58.919
I try to measure success on literally finishing, like delivering.

01:18:58.919 --> 01:19:00.919
So my wife and I are a little bit different.

01:19:00.919 --> 01:19:04.919
I like the destination more so than the journey.

01:19:04.919 --> 01:19:08.919
So if it means changing around and having people contribute, that's cool.

01:19:08.919 --> 01:19:09.919
That's the journey.

01:19:09.919 --> 01:19:10.919
That's great for me.

01:19:10.919 --> 01:19:15.919
I love people doing that piece as long as the destination is kind of successful.

01:19:15.919 --> 01:19:17.919
So that's kind of a bit of my mantra.

01:19:17.919 --> 01:19:21.919
I care less about how we get there.

01:19:21.919 --> 01:19:28.919
But to summarize, being goofy, like if you're okay with being goofy, laughing a whole bunch,

01:19:28.919 --> 01:19:32.919
trying to tell a story and breaking it down into like kind of analogies

01:19:32.919 --> 01:19:36.919
and understanding your target audience is what I did.

01:19:36.919 --> 01:19:40.919
Mentorship, no, I'm still – I had a great person, like one individual,

01:19:40.919 --> 01:19:43.919
but really my mentors have been movies.

01:19:43.919 --> 01:19:45.919
I just love movies.

01:19:45.919 --> 01:19:49.919
So just using like, hey, one of the things I helped out with a friend,

01:19:49.919 --> 01:19:51.919
she was really scared for an interview.

01:19:51.919 --> 01:19:54.919
I'm like, one of the ones that I use all the time.

01:19:54.919 --> 01:19:59.919
So here's a movie plug of my approach is 8 Mile with Eminem.

01:19:59.919 --> 01:20:03.919
So for those of you who have watched it, you're going to know what I'm about to say.

01:20:03.919 --> 01:20:09.919
For those of you who don't, fast forward all the way to the last half an hour of the movie.

01:20:09.919 --> 01:20:12.919
I try to do everything like Mom's Spaghetti, the last rap battle.

01:20:12.919 --> 01:20:17.919
I take away all their ammunition and just kind of like put it out there at the beginning.

01:20:17.919 --> 01:20:20.919
So what I do, right, is you just try to own it and, hey, yeah, you're right,

01:20:20.919 --> 01:20:24.919
I don't know anything, but can we talk about what we need to do instead?

01:20:24.919 --> 01:20:29.919
So you just remove all the barriers at the beginning and just totally be funny about it.

01:20:29.919 --> 01:20:35.919
And if people aren't laughing, it's like, great, now I know I don't want to work with you.

01:20:35.919 --> 01:20:38.919
I love that you referenced 8 Mile.

01:20:38.919 --> 01:20:43.919
I said in the chat, when we make – so we are making this data science hangout site

01:20:43.919 --> 01:20:45.919
where you can see all the recordings and resources.

01:20:45.919 --> 01:20:49.919
So I might have to add that to the recommendation.

01:20:49.919 --> 01:20:53.919
I think that's actually a great point, that rhymes.

01:20:53.919 --> 01:20:58.919
And it's really bad that I forgot to speak from last week's name.

01:20:58.919 --> 01:21:05.919
But it's about understanding that we're not perfect.

01:21:05.919 --> 01:21:11.919
And it's going, yes, I know I can't do this now.

01:21:11.919 --> 01:21:13.919
But you give me the time.

01:21:13.919 --> 01:21:17.919
I'm dedicated enough to learn this, and I will get there.

01:21:17.919 --> 01:21:23.919
And I think that's one of the biggest skills, that showing that you're vulnerable,

01:21:23.919 --> 01:21:26.919
showing you're not perfect.

01:21:26.919 --> 01:21:31.919
And it comes across, like Ryan's not deliberately doing this,

01:21:31.919 --> 01:21:34.919
but he's saying that he doesn't know everything.

01:21:35.919 --> 01:21:37.919
You can hear my dogs.

01:21:37.919 --> 01:21:40.919
Oh, no, I love dogs.

01:21:40.919 --> 01:21:44.919
But yeah, it's that vulnerability and knowing that you're not perfect.

01:21:44.919 --> 01:21:47.919
And that's came across a lot.

01:21:47.919 --> 01:21:48.919
Thanks.

01:21:48.919 --> 01:21:54.919
